<div id="review_497912397" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/497912397" />
    <a title="Ann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/406595-ann"><img alt="Ann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1212144874p2/406595.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/497912397?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann" href="/user/show/406595-ann">Ann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/406595-ann?shelf=2012">2012</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer497912397" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1895441277653746619">I&apos;m a longtime fan of Jon Clinch, and though this book is very different in feel from Finn and Kings of the Earth, I liked it just as much. Without minimizing or diluting the horrors of Auschwitz, Clinch demonstrates how literature can show us the light and shadows in even the darkest experiences. Clinch&apos;s characters bring us close to the story, and while we feel the pain and know what lies ahead, we keep reading, because we care. </span>
  <span id="freeText1895441277653746619" style="display:none">I'm a longtime fan of Jon Clinch, and though this book is very different in feel from Finn and Kings of the Earth, I liked it just as much. Without minimizing or diluting the horrors of Auschwitz, Clinch demonstrates how literature can show us the light and shadows in even the darkest experiences. Clinch's characters bring us close to the story, and while we feel the pain and know what lies ahead, we keep reading, because we care. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1895441277653746619" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


